<Base title="Methodology" wide>
  <p class="kicker">Methodology</p>
  <h1>How we build the atlas</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    AUSPEX is a doctrine-tagged atlas of state-sponsored cyber events.
    This page documents the choices we make so analysts can decide how
    much weight to put on any claim.
  </p>

  <nav class="toc">
    <strong>Contents</strong>
    <ol>
      <li><a href="#wedge">The doctrine wedge</a></li>
      <li><a href="#model">The data model</a></li>
      <li><a href="#confidence">Confidence labels</a></li>
      <li><a href="#sourcing">Sourcing hierarchy</a></li>
      <li><a href="#sec9">Doctrine without attribution</a></li>
      <li><a href="#attribution">Attribution norms and limits</a></li>
      <li><a href="#naming">Naming reconciliation</a></li>
      <li><a href="#editorial">Editorial process</a></li>
      <li><a href="#evals">Engine evaluations</a></li>
      <li><a href="#dont">What we don't do</a></li>
      <li><a href="#limits">Known limits</a></li>
      <li><a href="#stability">Versioning and stability</a></li>
      <li><a href="#license">License and contact</a></li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  <section id="wedge">
    <h2>The doctrine wedge</h2>
    <p>
      The tier-one vendor threat-intel ecosystem — Mandiant, Microsoft
      MSTIC, CrowdStrike, Recorded Future, Kaspersky GReAT — indexes
      cyber activity by <em>what happened</em> (IOCs, TTPs, vendor
      cluster names). Strategic-studies institutions — CSIS, RUSI, RAND,
      IISS — index the <em>why</em>: grand strategies, doctrines,
      timeline pressures. Nobody indexes events <em>against</em>
      doctrines as a first-class relationship. That join is the AUSPEX
      product.
    </p>
    <p>
      Concretely: every cyber event in the atlas can carry any number of
      links to specific doctrine pillars or programs, each with its own
      confidence level and explicit reasoning. <strong>The link can stand
      without a named actor.</strong> That asymmetry — doctrine
      attribution as decoupled from actor attribution — is the editorial
      property the model is built to support.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="model">
    <h2>The data model</h2>
    <p>
      The atlas is a directed-graph of typed entities, stored as YAML
      files in a git repository, regenerated into a queryable index on
      every build. The full schema lives in
      <code>docs/DATA_MODEL.md</code> in the repo; the short version:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Nation-state</strong> → <strong>Service</strong> →
        <strong>Actor</strong>. Hierarchical attribution chain. A
        service may have sub-services (GRU has 26165, 74455, 54777;
        FSB has Centers 16 and 18). An actor may have multiple
        services in the additional-service list when public reporting
        is split.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Doctrine</strong> → <strong>Pillar</strong> →
        <strong>Program</strong>. Doctrines have a published or
        inferred top-level frame (MIC2025, Foreign Policy Concept
        2023, Resistance Axis, Byungjin, NCS 2023). Pillars are the
        sector-or-thematic decomposition; programs are named
        initiatives within a pillar. Events tag at the most specific
        level the source supports.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Event</strong>. The atomic unit. Carries <em>attributions</em>
        (one or more, each with attributing-org), <em>doctrine_links</em>
        (one or more, each with confidence and reasoning),
        <em>targets</em> (target_id + country), <em>anticipated_timeline_markers</em>,
        and <em>sources</em>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Target</strong>. Either a sector (with optional
        country code), an organization (orgs/&lt;slug&gt;), or named
        infrastructure (infra/&lt;slug&gt;). Sector slugs follow the
        hierarchical taxonomy at <code>atlas/sectors/sectors.yaml</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Source</strong>. Every claim has at least one. Sources
        carry publisher, kind (govt-primary / cert-advisory /
        vendor-research / think-tank / journalism / academic /
        leaked-doc / book), tier (primary / secondary / tertiary),
        URL, archive_url.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Timeline marker</strong>. Anchors for predictive
        analysis: Davidson Window 2027, the 8th Party Congress
        defense-plan endpoint (2025), JCPOA snapback (2025),
        Soleimani assassination anniversary, election cycles.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>External references</strong>. Each actor carries
        <code>external_refs</code> pointing into MITRE ATT&amp;CK
        Groups (G####), MISP Galaxy (UUID), and where present, Malpedia
        and ETDA. These let analysts join AUSPEX against existing
        canonical registries.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Policy action</strong>. External pressure events that
        historically correlate with state-sponsored cyber tasking:
        sanctions, indictments, export controls, treaties, summits,
        elections, party congresses, Olympics, military exercises,
        weapons tests, anniversaries. Forward calendar through 2029
        and a historical record from 2014. Events can be linked to
        policy actions via the <code>responds_to</code> /
        <code>anticipates</code> edges; the
        <a href="/research/policy-response">policy-response correlator</a>
        publishes conditional statistics on the historical lag
        distribution between (action_type, target_state) classes
        and subsequent cyber events.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="confidence">
    <h2>Confidence labels</h2>

    <h3>Doctrine-link confidence</h3>
    <p>
      Every <code>doctrine_link</code> on an event carries one of three
      labels. The label discipline is the central editorial commitment
      of the atlas.
    </p>
    <table class="conf-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Label</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="confidence confidence-attested">attested</span></td>
          <td>
            The attributing government or vendor <strong>explicitly named the
            strategic goal</strong>. Treasury's April 2022 designation of
            the Ronin Bridge theft to Lazarus stating that "the funds
            support the DPRK's weapons of mass destruction and ballistic
            missile programs" is the canonical pattern. FBI Director
            Wray's House testimony naming Volt Typhoon as Taiwan-conflict
            pre-positioning is another. We do not upgrade; if a source
            stopped short, we stop short.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="confidence confidence-strongly-inferred">strongly inferred</span></td>
          <td>
            Victim sector, timing, technique, and known actor mission
            align with a named doctrine pillar with no major alternative
            explanation. Used when the doctrinal logic is well-documented
            in primary doctrinal writing (MCF strategists on
            civil-infrastructure targeting, IRGC on
            forward-defense-via-cyber) but the specific attributing
            source did not articulate the strategic goal.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="confidence confidence-plausible">plausible</span></td>
          <td>
            The link fits the doctrine, but other explanations exist.
            Surfaced with an explicit <code>counter_explanation</code>
            field on the event so the reader sees both readings. Most
            commonly used for retroactive framings (e.g., pre-2022
            Russian-aligned ransomware framed as criminal-state
            symbiosis is plausible — the doctrine
            <em>crystallized</em> post-invasion, the activity preceded
            it).
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Attribution confidence</h3>
    <p>
      Separately, each attribution row carries the
      <em>attributing organization's own</em> confidence at the time of
      attribution, in the ICD-203 vocabulary:
    </p>
    <table class="conf-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>high</code></td><td>Strong evidence; alternatives have been considered and ruled out.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>moderate</code></td><td>Credible but not conclusive; alternatives remain.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>low</code></td><td>Fragmentary; possible but not preferred among alternatives.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>AUSPEX assessment</h3>
    <p>
      Finally, each attribution row carries an
      <code>auspex_assessment</code> recording where we land:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <code>concur</code> (default) — we agree with the attributing
        organization's call.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>concur-with-caveat</code> — we agree but note context.
        Used when an attribution was retrospective (Salt Typhoon's
        2023 IOS XE campaign got proper attribution only in the 2025
        AA25-239A advisory) or when cluster boundaries are unsettled.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>partial</code> — we agree with part of the attribution
        but not all of it (e.g., service-level attribution holds but
        the specific actor cluster doesn't).
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>contested</code> — material disagreement among credible
        sources. Surfaced explicitly so the reader knows.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      We publish our second-order assessment because it is part of the
      value buyers can't easily reproduce — but we always show the
      attributing organization's own framing first.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="sourcing">
    <h2>Sourcing hierarchy</h2>
    <p>
      Sources are ranked into three tiers. The ranking determines what
      we are willing to label <em>attested</em>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Tier 1 — Primary government documents.</strong>
        Treasury OFAC SDN listings and press releases (jyXXX, sbXXXX
        series), DOJ press releases and unsealed indictments, CISA /
        FBI / NSA advisories (AAYY-NNNL series, IC3 advisories),
        ODNI Annual Threat Assessment, Treasury / State / Commerce
        SDN actions, Five Eyes joint advisories, foreign-ministry
        statements where attributive language is direct. These are
        the only sources that can carry an <em>attested</em>
        doctrine-link label.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tier 2 — Authoritative vendor research and Five Eyes
        partner agencies.</strong> Mandiant (Google Cloud TAG),
        Microsoft MSTIC and Threat Intelligence Center, CrowdStrike
        Falcon Intelligence, Recorded Future Insikt Group, Kaspersky
        GReAT, ESET Research, SentinelLabs, Volexity, Palo Alto Unit
        42, Trend Micro Zero Day Initiative, Proofpoint, Talos,
        Dragos and Claroty (ICS-focused), Group-IB. Plus NCSC-UK,
        CCCS Canada, ACSC Australia, BSI Germany, ANSSI France,
        JPCERT/CC, NIS Korea, INCD Israel. These can carry
        <em>strongly inferred</em> doctrine-link labels and ICD-203
        confidence ratings we generally concur with.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tier 3 — Independent / open research and journalism.</strong>
        MITRE ATT&amp;CK Groups, MISP Galaxy, CSIS Significant Cyber
        Incidents, ASPI International Cyber Policy Centre, RUSI, CEPA,
        CNAS, Atlantic Council DFRLab, FDD, Lawfare, The Record,
        CyberScoop, Wired, Reuters, NYT, WaPo, Krebs on Security, plus
        the Chainalysis / TRM Labs / Elliptic crypto-tracing trio.
        These can support <em>plausible</em> labels and provide
        corroborating context but not standalone primary attestation.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Where sources conflict, we surface the conflict in the
      <code>notes</code> field and pick the most rigorous tier-1
      reading. When a source's URL is unverified — typically Lawfare
      analysis pieces and committee-testimony transcripts whose
      canonical URLs change — we publish the source stub with the
      publisher and title set and the URL marked unverified rather
      than fabricate.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="sec9">
    <h2>§9: Doctrine without attribution</h2>
    <p>
      The atlas's most editorially distinct cell is the
      doctrine-tagged-but-unattributed event. The schema explicitly
      permits an event to carry one or more <code>doctrine_link</code>
      entries with no named actor.
    </p>
    <p>The black-flag cell exists for cases like these:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Estonia 2007 and Georgia 2008.</strong> Pro-Kremlin
        DDoS campaigns assessed by Estonian CERT, NATO CCDCOE, and
        US-CCU as state-coordinated; never legally proven. Doctrine
        link: Russian "near abroad" assertion. Actor: null.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The Romanian 2024 presidential interference.</strong>
        CSAT declassified attribution to "a state actor" without
        naming Russia. The event sits in the atlas with no actor and
        a strongly-inferred Russian-doctrine link.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Unattributed water-utility intrusions during PLA
        exercise windows.</strong> The atlas can tag these to the
        Taiwan-reunification pillar at <em>plausible</em> with no
        actor field populated, surfacing the doctrinal pattern even
        when individual events lack public attribution.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Operationally: actor attribution and doctrine attribution are
      independent decisions. Either can be empty. The interesting cell
      is <em>(no actor, doctrine linked)</em> — that is where AUSPEX
      makes claims tier-one vendor reporting structurally cannot.
    </p>
    <p>
      The black-flag cell also pre-empts the
      <em>i-SOON-style</em> problem: when attribution shifts from
      "unknown" to "MSS-via-contractor" years later (as it did when
      the i-SOON leak surfaced in February 2024), the doctrine tag
      was already correct and doesn't need to change.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="attribution">
    <h2>Attribution norms and limits</h2>
    <p>
      The atlas does not invent attribution. It records what attributing
      organizations have said, with our second-order assessment of
      whether the call holds.
    </p>

    <h3>Frameworks we use</h3>
    <p>
      Attribution decisions in the atlas are evaluated against the
      Diamond Model of Intrusion Analysis (Caltagirone, Pendergast,
      Betz) and Lockheed Martin's Cyber Kill Chain, both as evidence
      frameworks rather than as outcomes. Where an attributing source
      walks the Diamond corners explicitly (adversary, capability,
      infrastructure, victim), we generally <code>concur</code>. Where
      they assert without walking, we look for corroboration before
      moving past <code>concur-with-caveat</code>.
    </p>

    <h3>Known failure modes</h3>
    <p>The atlas treats these as first-order analytic risks:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>False flags.</strong> Olympic Destroyer (2018) is the
        canonical case — initial attribution to North Korea was
        deliberately seeded as misdirection by GRU Unit 74455. The
        atlas now flags every event with a <code>false_flag_risk</code>
        field. Predatory Sparrow is the inverse case: an Israeli (or
        Israel-aligned) operator whose tradecraft has at times been
        miscoded as Iranian by reflex; the atlas lists it under
        <code>actors/il/predatory-sparrow</code> with explicit
        not-Iranian flagging.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Criminal-state blur.</strong> Conti is the canonical
        case. The 2022 ContiLeaks exposed direct FSB Center-18
        liaison alongside an ordinary ransomware-as-a-service
        business. The atlas records actor-state relationships as
        operational rather than direct-control unless attestation is
        explicit. Russian-aligned ransomware actors carry plausible
        links to the post-2022 sanctions-response doctrine because
        the ecosystem tolerance is well-documented, but individual
        events generally do not carry attested doctrine links.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Contractor outsourcing.</strong> The i-SOON leak
        (February 2024) systematically documented PRC MSS
        provincial-bureau tasking through contractor firms. The same
        pattern recurs with Iran (Najee Technology, Afkar System,
        Rana Intelligence Computing), India (Appin Security, BellTroX
        / Dark Basin), and others. The atlas treats contractors as
        distinct actor entries with explicit parent-service
        attribution where DOJ or OFAC have named the relationship.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Multi-stage attribution.</strong> A single intrusion
        may be initial-access-broker A → ransomware-affiliate B →
        ransomware-brand C. Where public reporting names each stage,
        the atlas records each as a distinct attribution row.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Retroactive re-attribution.</strong> Salt Typhoon's
        2023 IOS XE campaign was attributed to PRC only retroactively
        via AA25-239A in 2025. The atlas marks the original event with
        <code>auspex_assessment: concur-with-caveat</code> and notes
        the lag.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="naming">
    <h2>Naming reconciliation</h2>
    <p>
      The same actor cluster routinely carries five or more names across
      vendors. Lazarus = Hidden Cobra (US CISA) = Labyrinth Chollima
      (CrowdStrike) = ZINC / Diamond Sleet (Microsoft) = TEMP.Hermit
      (Mandiant) = G0032 (MITRE) = Hastati Group (McAfee, historical).
    </p>
    <p>
      The atlas treats <strong>one canonical name per actor</strong>
      and a complete <code>aliases</code> table mapping the vendor
      names with an explicit <code>assigning_org</code> and
      <code>confidence</code> (equivalent / overlapping / disputed).
      Where vendor clusters genuinely don't line up — the Silk
      Typhoon / Hafnium / APT27 reconciliation problem — alias entries
      carry <em>overlapping</em> or <em>disputed</em> and the event
      attributions to the contested cluster carry <code>contested: true</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      We also publish each actor's <code>external_refs</code> with
      stable join keys into MITRE ATT&amp;CK Groups (G####) and MISP
      Galaxy (UUID). Analysts who already maintain their own taxonomy
      can join AUSPEX against it on either key.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="editorial">
    <h2>Editorial process</h2>
    <p>
      The atlas is hand-curated YAML in a versioned repository.
      Changes are reviewed before merge. Each event records the
      analyst who authored its doctrine links (internal-only field).
    </p>
    <p>The editorial pipeline for a new event:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Event is identified from a primary source (Tier 1 ideally,
        Tier 2 acceptable for emerging events). The source is written
        to <code>atlas/sources/&lt;publisher&gt;/&lt;date&gt;_&lt;slug&gt;.yaml</code> first.
      </li>
      <li>
        Actor attribution rows are written using only what the
        attributing source said. If the source named a service but not
        a specific cluster, <code>actor_id</code> is null and
        <code>service_id</code> is set.
      </li>
      <li>
        Doctrine links are drafted. Each carries explicit reasoning
        prose, an attesting source where one exists, and a
        counter-explanation where alternatives are reasonable.
      </li>
      <li>
        Targets are tagged with the most specific sector slug
        supported by the source, plus country code where applicable.
      </li>
      <li>
        The validator (<code>pnpm run validate</code>) is run.
        Dangling FK references are resolved before the event ships.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section id="evals">
    <h2>Engine evaluations — what we publish</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>What "accuracy" means here.</strong> Ground-truth labels are analyst-concurred
      <em>vendor attributions</em> — published accuracy measures agreement with that consensus,
      not with a verified oracle (vendor attribution carries its own unknown error rate).
      Leave-one-out / cross-validation numbers are <strong>retrodictive</strong>: training
      includes events before <em>and after</em> each held-out event, so they measure
      attribution of operations whose actors have corpus history — the
      <a href="/research/temporal-eval">temporal holdout</a> (train ≤ 2023, score 2024+,
      cold-start counted as miss) is the prospective figure. Prose summaries are
      analyst-written by someone who knew the attribution: literal actor names and
      doctrine-identifying tokens are scrubbed from the prose features, but framing vocabulary
      remains analyst-mediated — the fully prose-ablated bound (a few points below the deployed
      headline) is the conservative floor. Bootstrap CIs treat events as i.i.d.; events cluster by
      campaign and actor, so true intervals are somewhat wider (estimated design effect ≈ 2 → ~√2).
    </p>
    <p>
      Four prediction engines run over the atlas with backtests
      published on dedicated research pages:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <a href="/research/attribution-eval">Attribution</a> —
        predicts the most likely actor cluster from event features.
        Leave-one-out cross-validation. Top-1 / top-3 / top-5 hit
        rates plus Monte Carlo corpus-stability resampling.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/research/doctrine-eval">Doctrine prediction</a> —
        multi-label, predicts the strategic doctrine(s) an event
        serves. Top-K hit and recall@K, mAP.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/research/pillar-eval">Pillar prediction</a> —
        finer-resolution variant predicting specific within-doctrine
        pillars.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/research/joint-eval">Joint pair</a> — scores
        (actor × doctrine) candidate pairs together using
        co-occurrence as a confidence-calibration layer.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/research/temporal-eval">Temporal holdout</a> —
        the forward-prediction test. Train on events with
        <code>start_date ≤ 2023-12-31</code>, score every event
        afterwards cold, no per-event retraining.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/research/policy-response">Policy-response
        correlator</a> — for each policy-action class with ≥3
        historical instances, publishes the lag-window distribution
        of cyber events from the target state. Conditional
        statistics, not causal claims.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Supersession-equivalence in eval</h3>
    <p>
      Some doctrines supersede others (Byungjin → 8th Congress
      Defense Plan; NCS 2023 → 2026 Trump Cyber Strategy; FPC 2016
      → FPC 2023). When the supersession relationship is modeled in
      the atlas, the eval engines treat the supersession chain as a
      single equivalence class for hit-rate purposes — a top-1
      prediction of Byungjin when the truth tagged
      8th-Congress-Defense-Plan counts as correct, because they're
      the same operational program under sequential doctrinal frames.
      This is a fairness adjustment, not a model change. The
      adjustment is applied symmetrically and documented per
      research page.
    </p>

    <h3>Scoring conventions and leakage disclosures</h3>
    <p>
      Hit-rates use the <strong>null&nbsp;=&nbsp;miss</strong>
      convention: every labeled event is scored, and an event whose only
      true label has no other example in the corpus — structurally
      unrankable under leave-one-out — counts as a miss (reciprocal
      rank&nbsp;0), not an exclusion. This is the standard
      information-retrieval treatment and is applied identically across
      every engine and the MITRE / stacked baselines, so the numbers are
      directly comparable.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Attribution engine.</strong> Attribution is served by a
      <strong>ComplementNB</strong> base (Rennie et&nbsp;al. 2003 — designed for
      severe class imbalance, which the long tail of one-and-few-event actors
      exhibits) re-ranked by an L2 logistic stacker over discriminative
      meta-features (named-operator and target-org overlap, malware-lineage hit,
      campaign match, active-window). Operations-only top-1 is
      <strong>50.8%</strong> (ComplementNB base 44.2%&nbsp;→ +6.6&nbsp;pp from the
      re-ranker; 5-fold CV) on the 785-event corpus. The native scorer is validated
      against scikit-learn to the decimal, and the deployed model runs in
      <a href="/predict">/predict</a>, verified byte-identical browser-vs-server.
      The joint (actor&nbsp;×&nbsp;doctrine) engine also uses ComplementNB on the
      actor side (actorWeight&nbsp;2.0); joint-pair top-1 is <strong>38.0%</strong>
      (leave-one-out); doctrine and pillar remain the multi-hot Naive-Bayes engine.
    </p>
    <p>
      The corpus was first grown from 658 to 815 events to widen coverage — a
      <em>harder, longer-tailed</em> label space — and then the completed
      <strong>100% verification census</strong> removed fabricated and duplicate
      events, cleaning it to 785. Both moves lowered the headline, and both are
      integrity / composition effects rather than model regressions: growth added a
      thin long tail, and the census performed a <em>de-circularization</em> —
      removing the over-attributed and fabricated events the engines had partly
      memorized. (A corpus-growth experiment on the pre-census corpus confirmed the
      original-events accuracy was preserved exactly under expansion; the drops are
      composition, not model change.) Lifting the tail takes three levers — event
      <em>depth</em> per actor above the cross-validation threshold, source-grounded
      <em>feature richness</em>, and <em>discriminability</em> from same-niche
      neighbors; raw event count moves none. Doctrine (now <strong>62.8%</strong>),
      pillar (<strong>57.6%</strong>), and joint (<strong>38.0%</strong>) reflect the
      same harder, cleaner label space. Doctrine coverage is 76% of operations; the
      remaining ~24% are criminal / stateless operations with no strategic doctrine,
      plus a residual untagged tail.
    </p>
    <p>
      The attribution engine includes an editorial
      <code>campaign_id</code> feature: when an event is publicly
      reported as part of a named campaign, that linkage is genuine
      analyst-available evidence. Because a single-actor campaign tag can
      effectively encode the attribution, we publish the attribution
      hit-rate <em>both with and without</em> this feature — the ablated
      figure is the lower bound on genuinely novel, untagged events. The
      algorithmically-inferred campaign clusters are label-blind by
      construction, and a held-out event's own inferred-campaign
      membership is suppressed while it is scored, so a cluster it helped
      form cannot leak its label back.
    </p>
    <p>
      The hierarchical service-prior (Empirical&nbsp;Bayes,
      λ&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.2) smooths the multinomial count features of rare
      actors toward their service's shape under leave-one-out;
      presence-only TTP and malware signals are deliberately not smoothed
      (each actor keeps only its own observed tradecraft). TF-IDF prose
      weighting uses a corpus-global document frequency (a fixed,
      label-free vocabulary statistic) — and in leave-one-out the held-out
      event is excluded from its own document-frequency, so its prose terms
      are weighted by training-only DF. Actor names and aliases are scrubbed
      from the prose vocabulary, so an analyst summary naming the actor cannot
      leak the attribution label (this had affected a large majority of events;
      removing it moved the operations-only headline by under 1&nbsp;pp, the engine
      leaning instead on operators, campaign, and malware). Corpus-stability resampling
      uses a seeded generator so the figure is reproducible build-to-build.
    </p>

    <h3>Operations vs. meta events</h3>
    <p>
      The atlas logs two kinds of entry: cyber <em>operations</em>
      (intrusions, theft, disruption, influence, pre-positioning, …) and
      <em>meta / announcement</em> events (doctrine publications, sanctions
      and attribution notices, policy / law-enforcement actions). The
      prediction engines exist to infer the strategic frame and actor of
      <em>operations</em>; predicting the doctrine of a doctrine-publication
      is a different — and largely circular — task. So the 137 pure-meta
      events (every <code>incident_type</code> a meta type) are
      <strong>excluded from the eval label sets</strong> but kept in the
      <strong>training</strong> corpus (a doctrine publication is the
      doctrine's defining text) and in the atlas (timeline, provenance,
      narrative). An event with any operational <code>incident_type</code>
      counts as an operation even if it is also documented. Excluding meta
      events <em>raises</em> the doctrine headline slightly — they are
      off-task for an operation-trained engine, not easy wins — so we
      publish both the operations-only and all-events numbers on the
      research page.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="dont">
    <h2>What we don't do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Invent attribution.</strong> If no public source has
        attributed an event, we don't either. We tag the doctrine if
        the circumstantial case is strong; we leave the actor null.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Attribute counter-operations to their target.</strong>
        When an event <em>is</em> a state counter-action — an
        infrastructure takedown or seizure, a law-enforcement disruption,
        a sanctions designation, or a bounty — the operation in the event
        was carried out by a law-enforcement / sanctioning / diplomatic
        body, not by a tracked threat actor. So <code>actor_id</code> is
        null (the acting body sits in <code>attributing_org</code>; the
        targeted actor is named in the summary), and the event is kept out
        of the attribution label space — it is not a "who did it?" puzzle.
        Events that instead <em>document</em> a threat actor's own
        operations (an indictment detailing the intrusions, a vendor
        attribution report) keep the actor.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Manufacture specificity.</strong> If a source says
        "an MSS-linked group" we tag it that way (service-level
        attribution); we do not upgrade to a specific cluster.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Anonymize sources.</strong> Every claim has at least
        one source slug pointing at a source file. Source files carry
        publisher, title, URL.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Fabricate URLs.</strong> Where the canonical URL for a
        cited piece can't be verified, the source file is written with
        <code>url: null</code> and a <code>notes</code> field that
        explains the gap. Better honest than fake-precise.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Take vendor product placement.</strong> AUSPEX has no
        commercial relationship with any vendor named in the atlas.
        We rely on what those vendors publish; we do not edit on
        request.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Coordinate publication with attributing agencies.</strong>
        We track government attributions as primary sources but we
        are not embedded with, briefed by, or pre-clearing through
        any IC component.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="limits">
    <h2>Known limits</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Post-April-2024 DPRK monitoring blackout.</strong> The
        UN 1718 Panel of Experts mandate ended 30 April 2024 after a
        Russian veto. The successor MSMT (Multilateral Sanctions
        Monitoring Team, May 2024 stand-up) has produced limited
        outputs. DPRK financial-theft figures in the atlas after
        mid-2024 are likely under-counted relative to ground truth.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Classified-side asymmetry on US operations.</strong>
        US cyber <em>doctrine</em> is publicly published in detail.
        US cyber <em>operations</em> are largely classified, with
        public knowledge coming from leaks (Snowden 2013, Shadow
        Brokers 2016–17, Vault 7 2017) and rare declassifications
        (Olympic Games / Stuxnet, the IRA disruption, KV-Botnet / Volt
        Typhoon takedown). The atlas's US-operations corpus is
        therefore biased toward leak-attributed material; ordinary
        US offensive cyber that has not leaked is invisible.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Inference standards for non-doctrine-publishing
        states.</strong> Iran, DPRK, and several of the v0.1 additions
        (Vietnam, Pakistan, Belarus) do not publish formal cyber
        doctrine documents. Their doctrine entries in the atlas carry
        <code>status: inferred</code> and the inference is
        reconstructed from constitutional documents, supreme-leader
        speeches, and operational pattern. The atlas labels this
        openly; downstream consumers should weight inferred doctrines
        differently from attested ones.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Cluster naming churn.</strong> Microsoft renamed its
        entire taxonomy in April 2023 (Typhoon = PRC, Blizzard = RU,
        Sandstorm = IR, Sleet = DPRK, Hail = SK, Tempest =
        financially-motivated criminal, Tsunami = private-sector
        offensive). CrowdStrike, Mandiant, Talos, Kaspersky have
        their own conventions. Secureworks's BRONZE/IRON/COBALT/NICKEL
        taxonomy is at risk after the February 2025 Sophos acquisition.
        The atlas pins to MITRE ATT&amp;CK Group IDs (G####) and MISP
        Galaxy UUIDs where present because those are the most stable
        join keys.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Continuous-compromise actors under-counted.</strong>
        Kimsuky and APT37 operate through continuous spear-phishing
        rather than discrete campaigns; their event-row counts in the
        atlas systematically under-represent their volume. A
        <code>Campaign</code> entity is planned for v0.2 to capture
        this.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Israeli, Saudi, UAE, French, and other allied-state
        offensive operations.</strong> Where attribution is public, we
        include them (Predatory Sparrow under IL with no formal
        service). Most allied offensive activity is not public
        enough to make the atlas; absence here does not mean absence
        in reality.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="stability">
    <h2>Versioning and stability</h2>
    <p>
      The atlas schema is documented in <code>docs/DATA_MODEL.md</code>
      in the repository. Breaking schema changes bump
      <code>schema_version</code> in the <a href="/api/atlas.json">JSON
      dump</a>. The current schema version is <code>0.1</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Slugs are <strong>stable forever once published</strong>. If we
      get a slug wrong, we leave the old slug as an alias and add a
      new canonical. Renames break analyst code; we won't do them.
    </p>
    <p>
      Event entries are <em>updatable</em> as new disclosure
      arrives — late-breaking attributions, additional doctrine
      links, late-arriving source citations. Material updates carry
      an analyst note.
    </p>
    <p>
      The atlas YAML repository is the canonical source. The site, the
      JSON API, and the RSS feed are derived. If you need to integrate
      AUSPEX into your own tooling, prefer the <a href="/api/atlas.json">JSON
      dump</a> over scraping HTML.
    </p>
  </section>

